        "title": "Foreign Function Interface",
        "theory": "## Calling C from Rust\nRust can talk to other languages (mostly C). This is called FFI.\n\nYou have to use `extern \"C\"` to define the C functions you want to call, and you MUST call them inside an `unsafe` block because Rust can't guarantee that the C code is safe.\n\n```rust\nextern \"C\" {\n    fn abs(input: i32) -> i32;\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    unsafe {\n        println!(\"Absolute value of -3 according to C: {}\", abs(-3));\n    }\n}\n```",
